stylometry:
Normal probability distribution

Also known as the normal curve it is used extensively in statistics and probability. It is the bell curve. it is symmetrical. It allows the user the usage of a set of tools many other probability distributions do not, the z-score and confidence interval. This helps in many statisical calculations. The normal curve does not account for a skew however, so if your data is skewed then the normal curve would not be an accurate distribution to use. Also the normal curve uses negative numbers, which generally is not a problem, but the demand for a product cannot be a negative number. Generally this issue works itself out but it is a problem the user should be aware of. The normal curve deals with a mean in the center, the mean is distributed by the standard deviation symmetrically on either side. The area under the curve can be taken and a z score can be obtained which is used in many equations dealing with probability and statistics. Confidence intervals are also used often with normal distributions.
